for the “Blood” Music Video Premiere !!!! 🩸

The Blood music video is out now. 🩸
It meant a lot to me to be able to depict how I see this song in my head and show exactly the kind of behavior I wrote this song about. 
With an abusive, alcoholic narcissist, you try to reason with them. You cater to their ego by quietly bringing up something that is bothering you about their behavior. “You don’t hold back, you don’t play nice”. That doesn’t land like you thought it would and they, not so kindly, put you back in your place. 
You try to set boundaries hoping they might respect you for standing up for yourself. “You go too far, and you get too close”. 
Then all of a sudden, you’re not sure if it’s even worth the fight, so you put yourself back in your place. “I hold my tongue, swallow my pride, and stay”.
They silently hold power over you, daring you to make another move and see what happens. Because… “What are *you* gonna do?” 
Finally, you’ve had enough. You stand up, give them exactly what they have given you, and turn into the monster that they are just so that they could turn around and say, “You’re crazy.” 
You realize that there is nothing you can do to win this fight. Nobody will win this fight. The only answer is to leave. 
🩸link in bio🩸
you’ll make it out okay, I promise. ♥️ love y’all.

Oftentimes, in movies we see what a dysfunctional relationship looks like, what an abuser looks like; typically, a gruff looking drunkard, a jobless ‘loser’ living in a trailer. Something very stereotypical. 
But in my experience, it looks a lot different. To me, it looks like the prettiest, wealthiest homes with the dinner table set to perfection, a homemade pie, crystal glasses and refined whiskey.  The husband just got home from work, still wearing his suit.  In public, he looks distinguished, a well-respected man. Behind closed doors, he is a monster feeding off a power that he holds over her.  That is what a ‘loser’ looks like to me.

Watch “Blood” on YouTube Now.

When I was thinking of ideas for a music video for this song, I thought the song pretty much spoke for itself and we could just tell the story of a girl leaving her no-good boyfriend for the big city only to be going to work at a diner every day. 

But when thinking of the line “But her small town pretty didn’t play in the city too well”…I thought, what if, instead of a regular ole gal, we had a drag queen be the main character? And we had this tongue-in-cheek, playful video where no one actually sees her as a drag queen and we shoot the video as if we were telling the story of this “simple girl” working in a diner, who dreams of a more glamorous life.✨

Not sure I can wait til Sunday at midnight to release this. ♥️☕️🥓🍳

Tour with @morganwademusic has come to an end. 15 dates in the books. I drove, I flew, I sound checked, I set up merch, I put my face on, I played the show, took a million selfies, and sold my merch til they closed the doors every. single. night. It was really hard work but I was energized after every show each night and woke up ready to do it all over again. Even in the biggest rooms I’ve ever played, y’all got so quiet for just me and my guitar and let me tell my stories and sing songs you’ve never heard before and as a songwriter, those kind of audiences are all you ever want.  @morganwademusic although we were both busy little gals this whole time and didn’t get to hang, it was a real privilege to get to be on this tour, work with your *incredible* band and crew, and play in front of your audience. You’ve surrounded yourself with a whole bunch of badasses and I’m just gonna tell myself that you put me on the tour bc you think I’m one too. 🙃
If you’re new here and discovered me on this tour, I hope you come and see me when I come back to your neck of the woods and bring all your friends too. 
I told the story of my song “it won’t always be this way” a lot on this tour and talked about a time where I was having a hard time seeing the light at the end of the tunnel. But this run brought a whole new meaning to that phrase to me, because each night I looked around and realized, this won’t last forever and had to remind myself that I needed to soak in every second of this spectacular tour because it won’t always be this way. ❤️‍🔥

The songs from What Else Can She Do are from a time in my life where I felt really hopeless. During that time, I turned to a Secret Sisters song when I really needed some comfort and peace. I would lay in bed flat on my back and turn on this song when I felt like I couldn’t take it anymore. I would let the tears roll down my cheeks and into my ears and after listening a few times through, I would start to believe that tomorrow would, in fact, be kinder. 

My version of “Tomorrow Will Be Kinder” is out anywhere you listen to music. Share with a friend who might need it.

Cain’s Ballroom, you hold a very special place in my heart. ♥️Tulsa, Oklahoma, it’s good to be home.

Starting out as a young female artist, I was always told that I needed to get it going before I turned 30 because Other Girls chance for success would significantly go down once they reached that age, but it seems like for me that the moment I turned 30, things started to pick up and I started to see the seeds that I planted for the last 12 years finally come to bloom. I started 2023 out on tour with Morgan Wade alone in a minivan with nothing but my guitar, merch, and a bunch of almond butter packets. Then I got to play huge festivals & venues like Two Step Inn, Stagecoach, The Ryman, Red Rocks, The Grand Ole Opry, & Cains Ballroom. 
I sold out my first headlining shows, made my national TV debut, & recorded on a lot of different projects as well as worked on something of my own that I’ve dreamed up for some time.
I finally have the exact band that I have always wanted. They are the coolest, most talented, kind, grounded, hilarious and flat out fun group of Roadrunners that I have had the pleasure of making music with. I am lucky to have them join me on stage and follow my dreams with them by my side. I have family and friends around me that love and respect me, who love to see me shine as much as they love to rot on the couch with me. 
I have a husband that understands me and the intricacies of this life because we chase the same dream. He is my ride or die, my Buckaroo. And finally, I have the most deeply loving fans in the world. I get to see you dance with your friends in the crowd, share my stories, laugh through the pain, hear your beautiful voices sing my songs back to me, and hear or read stories of how my music has been the soundtrack to your life or helped you get through a dark time.

For each of these things, I am so grateful and know how lucky this Oklahoma girl is. Know that I don’t take it for granted and I’m gonna keep giving ya all I’ve got ESP after I turn 31. 

2024, I’m ready to go. 

Here’s my 2023, POV: Me.
